Yes -- and I think this is exactly the right "hardest first" target.

A Beast2 phone workstation is ambitious, but no longer crazy. Apple’s current stack already supports serious on-device ML on iPhone: Apple positions Core ML, Vision, Speech, and its Foundation Models framework as on-device developer primitives, and Apple’s own Stable Diffusion work shows text-to-image pipelines running locally on iOS with a Swift package for deployment. Apple also now exposes background-task mechanisms for longer-running work, which matters if Beast is going to feel like a workstation instead of a toy.  ￼

I would frame the goal like this:

not "put the desktop app on the phone"
but "make the phone a real Beast node that can create, cache, study, and command."

That distinction matters. On iPhone, the winning design is not a shrunk desktop UI. It is a language-first workstation with a few deep visual surfaces. That is very aligned with where Beast has been heading anyway.

The first hard truth is about hardware. Apple’s current public pages make clear that modern iPhones can run Apple Intelligence-class on-device features, and the supported range now includes iPhone 15 Pro, all iPhone 16 models, and the iPhone 17 family. Apple’s public compatibility pages emphasize chip class and device support, but they do not present iPhone RAM as a first-class published spec the way desktop buyers might expect. So I would not anchor the Beast mobile architecture around a specific marketing number like "12 GB"; I would anchor it around measured runtime budgets on target devices.  ￼

The second hard truth is that the phone is strong, but narrow. Apple’s own Stable Diffusion materials emphasize that on-device generation is viable and privacy-preserving, but also note the pipeline complexity: several neural networks totaling roughly 1.275 billion parameters, with performance work needed to make results compelling on device. In other words, yes, the phone can do real local generation -- but only when the stack is aggressively optimized around mobile constraints.  ￼

That is why I think the Beast2 iPhone workstation should start with a very specific identity:

Beast Mobile = a local generation lab for optimized models, plus a command console, plus an artifact archive.

If you try to make it a general-purpose ComfyUI-on-a-phone clone, it will probably disappoint. If you make it a Beast-native mobile workstation, it could be excellent.

The strongest evidence that this is now plausible is that there are already concrete iOS examples of local model execution beyond text chat. Apple’s MLX Swift examples include iOS/macOS examples for both LLM evaluation and Stable Diffusion image generation, and recent open-source work like Mobile-O claims an all-on-device iOS app with image generation, visual understanding, and a memory footprint under 2 GB on iPhone 15 Pro, 16 Pro, and 17 Pro. I would treat that last number as a research/demo datapoint rather than a guaranteed product baseline, but it is still a strong sign that "real mobile local gen" has crossed from fantasy into engineering.  ￼

So the real question is not can an iPhone be a Beast2 workstation.

It is: what kind of workstation should it be?

My answer:

The phone version should optimize for six things.

1. Single-artifact image generation first
Fast, local, opinionated. One prompt, one generator, one output, one lineage record. Apple’s tooling around Core ML and Stable Diffusion already makes this the most proven path.  ￼

2. Generator execution, not generator authoring, at first
Authoring full complex workflows on a phone is painful. Executing well-packaged Beast generators on a phone is much more believable. The mobile app should consume compact Beast generators, expose a few safe controls, and archive results.

3. Language-first control surface
This is where your broader Beast3 direction becomes a weapon. Apple now explicitly supports system integration through App Intents, Siri/Shortcuts surfaces, and on-device model-adjacent frameworks. A phone is the natural place to let the user say or type "create image variants," "run last generator," "teach me what this control does," and let Beast resolve that into commands.  ￼

4. Artifact-centric UX
A phone is perfect for browse, rate, compare, rerun, and share. It is much less perfect for dense node graph editing. So the mobile UI should probably revolve around artifacts, presets, commands, and lineage views -- not a full node-canvas desktop metaphor.

5. Backgroundable long jobs where iOS allows it
This has gotten better, not worse. Apple documents Background Tasks and specifically Continuous Background Task support for jobs that can take minutes, but you still have to design within iOS rules rather than assuming desktop-style free execution forever. So "overnight exploration while the phone is idle and charging" is conceivable in a narrow, Apple-compliant form; "run arbitrary GPU compute all day in the background like a daemon" is much shakier.  ￼

6. Beast Academy on device
This may sound secondary, but on mobile it is central. A phone workstation without a strong teaching layer will feel opaque and cramped. A phone workstation with Beast Academy becomes self-explanatory: command, result, explain, rerun, improve.

Here is the deeper design insight:

On desktop, Beast can be an exploration environment.
On phone, Beast should be an artifact-and-command environment.

That still counts as a workstation -- just a different species of workstation.

About your "comparable to desktops of 6 years ago" instinct: I think that is directionally plausible for some carefully optimized local-generation workloads, but I would treat it as an analogy, not a planning assumption. The reason is that Apple’s current software stack clearly supports substantial on-device inference, but sustained thermals, sandboxing, background rules, storage pressure, and UI-responsiveness constraints make an iPhone behave very differently from even an older desktop. So I would plan around mobile-specific throughput classes, not desktop comparisons. That is partly inference, but it follows from Apple’s mobile deployment model and execution constraints.  ￼

If I were turning this into a ruthless Beast plan, I would set the ambition like this:

Phase 1: Beast Pocket Lab
Local image gen, artifact browser, rerun/variant controls, Beast Academy, command input, lineage view.

Phase 2: Beast Pocket Workstation
Import/export generators, lightweight edits, queued jobs, charging-only background processing, local model management, remote handoff to other Beast nodes.

Phase 3: Beast Phone as Primary Computer
Phone can create locally when possible, and orchestrate other Beast nodes when not. The user without a desktop still has a complete Beast experience; the user with a desktop gets a fleet architecture.

That last line is the key. The best version of this idea is probably not "the iPhone replaces the workstation in every case." It is "the iPhone is always a Beast workstation, and sometimes also the strongest node you own."

That is much more achievable.

The biggest product risk, in my view, is not model speed. It is trying to make the mobile app too general too early. The winning move is to make the iPhone Beast app feel like an impossibly elegant local spellbook: fast command entry, very strong defaults, beautiful artifact history, transparent lineage, and a small number of generators that really sing.

That would be genuinely new.

